<p>

In the lintel of  <saint wordnetid="110546850" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../938/54938.xml">
St. Nikolas' (Agios Nikolaos)</link></saint>
 old church, there is an embossed crown of the 15th century. Also in the church dedicated to the <look wordnetid="100877127" confidence="0.8">
<observation wordnetid="100879759" confidence="0.8">
<sensory_activity wordnetid="100876737" confidence="0.8">
<sensing wordnetid="100876874" confidence="0.8">
<fundamental_quantity wordnetid="113575869" confidence="0.8">
<time wordnetid="115122231" confidence="0.8">
<time_period wordnetid="115113229" confidence="0.8">
<event wordnetid="100029378" confidence="0.8">
<festival wordnetid="115162388" confidence="0.8">
<day wordnetid="115123115" confidence="0.8">
<act wordnetid="100030358" confidence="0.8">
<psychological_feature wordnetid="100023100" confidence="0.8">
<activity wordnetid="100407535" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../383/343383.xml">
Dormition of the Virgin</link></activity>
</psychological_feature>
</act>
</day>
</festival>
</event>
</time_period>
</time>
</fundamental_quantity>
</sensing>
</sensory_activity>
</observation>
</look>
, there is a Venetian funerary monument (sarcophagus) dating back to the 16th century, in which there are unknown embossed blazons. One of those depicts a lion with a sword which probably illustrates "St. Mark’s lion", the symbol of <site wordnetid="108651247" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../616/32616.xml">
Venice</link></site>
. This specific embossed blazon is also present on the roof of the church, above the chancel.</p>

